A good hypothesis isn't a guess — it's a bet you're willing to lose.
If you can't imagine the world where you're wrong, and how you'd know, you don't have a hypothesis. You have an opinion with a question mark.

The 4-field contract (the only template I use)
Field	What it answers	What kills it
1. Belief	"We believe that [specific user] in [specific context] will [specific behavior] because [specific reason]."	Vague subjects ("users"), unbounded contexts ("when using the app"), or no causal because
2. Evidence needed	"We'll know we're right if we see [observable signal], and we'll know we're wrong if we see [counter-signal]."	Only describing the win condition. If you can't articulate what kills the hypothesis, it isn't falsifiable
3. Experiment	"We'll learn this by [smallest possible test] within [time box] for [cost]."	Experiments that take longer than the bet is worth, or require shipping the real thing to learn anything
4. Success criteria	"≥ X% of [N participants] do [Y] within [Z window], measured by [instrument]."	No number, no denominator, no time window, no measurement plan
If any one field is missing, the whole thing fails. That's the contract.

The 5 smell tests
A hypothesis is good if it is:

Falsifiable — there's a clear outcome that proves you wrong. ("Users will love it" — not falsifiable. "≥40% of trial users return within 7 days" — falsifiable.)
Specific — names a who, a what, a when, and a why. No "users", no "the product", no "soon".
Bounded — has a number, a denominator, and a time window.
Tests a real assumption — kills or confirms a belief you actually hold and that actually matters. (Not "water is wet"-tier obvious.)
Predicts a number — you should be able to write down the expected result before the experiment runs. If your prediction is "we'll see what happens," you're not hypothesizing, you're sightseeing.
Live transformation — using your retention example
❌ Bad hypothesis (your starting point):

"Better onboarding emails will improve retention."

What's wrong:

"Better" is undefined
"Improve" is unbounded
"Retention" is an unscoped metric
No who, no when, no how much, no falsifier
✅ Good hypothesis (4-field, sharpened):

Field	Filled in
Belief	We believe that new B2C trial users who don't activate within 24h will complete their first core action if we send a single behaviorally-triggered email at hour 18 highlighting the one feature their cohort uses most, because our churn interviews showed they forgot the product existed — not that they didn't understand it.
Evidence needed	We'll be right if D7 retention for the treatment cohort ≥ baseline + 4 percentage points (p<0.05). We'll be wrong if the lift is <2 points, or open rate is <15% (suggesting email is the wrong channel entirely).
Experiment	A/B test: 50/50 split on next 2,000 trial signups, control = current onboarding sequence, treatment = single triggered email at h18. Time box: 3 weeks. Cost: ~1 eng-week + 1 lifecycle-marketer day.
Success criteria	≥4pp lift in D7 retention in the treatment cohort over a 2,000-user sample within 21 days, measured via the existing retention dashboard cohort view.
See the difference? The first version is a wish. The second is a contract — you can run it, you can lose it, and either result teaches you something specific.

Common traps I'll catch you in
Trap	Sounds like	What to do instead
Solution-as-hypothesis	"We should build dark mode"	State the belief about user behavior the solution addresses
Tautology	"Users who want this will use it"	Predict unknown behavior, not the definition of the audience
Multi-variable mush	"If we redesign onboarding, change pricing, and add tooltips, retention will rise"	One variable per hypothesis. Otherwise you'll never know which lever moved the metric
Confirmation-only	"We'll know we're right if engagement goes up"	Always state the kill condition too
Vanity metric	"More signups"	Pick a metric tied to the belief. Signups don't prove a retention hypothesis
Unfalsifiable in practice	"≥1% lift over 12 months"	If you can't detect the effect within the time/sample you have, the hypothesis isn't testable — even if it's logically falsifiable
