Let me break some bad news with love: you don't know what your users want. You know what 80% of survey respondents told you they'd hypothetically do, in a moment when saying "yes" cost them nothing. Those are very different things.

The single most expensive sentence in product management
"The survey said they'd use it weekly."

Every PM who's ever shipped a feature into a graveyard has said this. The corpses are stacked deep.

Stated preference vs. revealed preference — the gap is enormous
Domain	Stated preference	Revealed preference	Gap
EV purchases (US, ~2018)	"Would consider an EV": ~60%	Actual EV market share: ~2%	~30x
Healthier eating (consumer surveys)	"I plan to eat healthier": 70%+	Behavior change after 90 days: ~10%	~7x
New feature usage in B2B SaaS (well-documented industry pattern)	"Would use weekly": 60–80%	Actual weekly active usage: 5–15%	~5–10x
The cleanest mental model: divide your stated-preference numbers by 5 to get a generous estimate of revealed-preference reality. Your "80% weekly" probably maps to ~10–20% will try it, ~5–10% will use it monthly, ~1–3% will use it weekly. That's still potentially worth building — but it's a wildly different business case.

What's actually wrong with your "evidence"
Problem	Why it bites you
Selection bias	Who answers product surveys? Engaged power users. Not representative of the install base. The 20% who didn't say yes are probably closer to your churn cohort
Social desirability bias	"Would you use a feature that helps you do your job better?" — saying no makes the respondent feel lazy or anti-progress. Yes is the default polite answer
Hypothetical-mode cognition	The brain in "imagining the future" mode is optimistic, idealized, frictionless. The brain in "Tuesday at 3pm with Slack open" mode is none of those things
Leading question framing	"Would you use [described in best light] weekly?" pre-loads the answer. The neutral version — "what's the chance you'd use this in a given week, vs. the alternatives you have today?" — gets very different numbers
"Weekly" is a fantasy frequency	People dramatically overestimate self-reported frequency for anything aspirational. Gym attendance, journaling, eating vegetables, using new tools — all consistently overstated
No competing alternatives in the question	Real adoption happens against your existing UI, against habits, against doing nothing. The survey didn't include "or just keep doing what you do today" as an option, did it?
Sunk-cost trap	You ran the survey. You want it to mean something. So now confirmation bias kicks in. That's the deepest problem — the survey is now psychological insurance for a build decision you've already half-made
What the survey is good for, and what it isn't
✅ Good for	❌ Not good for
Identifying that something in this space might matter	Justifying a build decision
Recruiting interview subjects (the 80% who said yes)	Sizing the opportunity
Generating hypotheses to test	Confirming hypotheses
Picking which problem to investigate	Picking which solution to ship
The survey is a flashlight pointed at a possible problem. It is not a contract.

The conversion: from "we know" → falsifiable hypothesis
Let me reframe what you actually have:

❌ What you said:

"We KNOW users want feature X — 80% would use it weekly."

✅ What's actually true:

"A self-selected subset of survey-responding users, when asked a leading hypothetical question with no competing alternatives or cost, told us they would use feature X weekly. From this, we hypothesize that some unknown fraction of our active user base — probably 5–15% based on industry stated-vs-revealed gaps — would use it at least monthly. We have not yet tested this with revealed-preference data."

That sentence is uglier. It's also true. And it leaves room for the experiment that would convert hypothesis into knowledge.

The cheapest experiment that could prove you wrong (and you should run it before you build)
The 24-hour painted-door test:

Field	Spec
Hypothesis	We believe ≥15% of weekly-active users will click on a "Feature X" affordance and submit intent within 14 days, because the survey signal reflects real (not just stated) demand.
Right	≥15% click-through AND ≥40% of clickers complete an intent form (use case, frequency expected, willingness to pay/upgrade)
Wrong	<8% click-through → survey was social-desirability noise. Kill the build.
Mid (8–15%)	Run a concierge experiment for 30 days before committing to engineering
Experiment	Add a "Feature X — coming soon, get early access" affordance in the primary nav for 100% of WAU. Modal: short form. Build cost: <1 eng-day. Time: 14 days
Sample	All WAU during window. Compare CTR by survey-respondent vs. non-respondent cohorts (the gap tells you a lot)
What you learn	Whether the 80% is real demand, social-desirability noise, or selection-bias artifact — before you spend a sprint building the feature
You can do this test in less time than it would take you to write the spec for feature X.

The bold version
The bold version of "they said they'd use it weekly" is:

"If we put a fake button for feature X in the product tomorrow and 95% of users walk past it for a week, will I have the courage to kill the project and apologize to the people I cited the 80% number to?"

That's the question to sit with. If the answer is no — if the survey result is now politically load-bearing — you don't have evidence anymore. You have a commitment device. And commitment devices don't validate hypotheses, they protect egos.

Where to next?
[AM] Assumption Mapping — let's surface every assumption stacked under "the survey proves demand." I count at least 6. Rank by lethality. Bet you "the 80% generalizes from respondents to install base" is the deadliest one
[HE] Hypothesis Engineering — convert your survey-derived belief into 2–3 properly falsifiable 4-field hypotheses with revealed-preference success criteria
[ED] Experiment Design — design the 14-day painted-door test above as a fully-spec'd experiment with sample sizes, decision rules, and the kill criterion pre-registered (so you can't move the goalposts when results come in)
My strong recommendation: [ED] first. Spend one engineering day on the painted-door test. If the click-through is honest and high — congratulations, you've upgraded your survey signal to revealed-preference evidence and you can now build with conviction. If it's low — you just saved your team a sprint and learned something true about your users.

The survey is a hypothesis. The painted door is a test. Don't confuse the two.

