The "AI for X" trap is the most expensive trap in 2026
When a PM says "what if we used AI to [verb] [noun]?" in 2026, here's what's almost always happening underneath:

The org is feeling AI-FOMO — boards, customers, or competitors are asking "what's your AI strategy?"
The team picks the most-obvious LLM-shaped feature in their domain
They reframe a brand/positioning problem as a product opportunity
They build it
It ships into a saturated market against well-funded specialists, with no unfair advantage, and 6 months of sunk eng cost
This isn't pessimism. This is the central pattern of 2024–2026 product graveyards.

Pressure-testing "AI to summarize meetings" specifically
This isn't a frontier idea. It's a saturated category. Look honestly at who you'd be competing with:

Competitor type	Examples	Their advantage over you
Standalone meeting AI	Otter, Fireflies, Granola, Read.ai, Fathom, Tactiq	Years of UX iteration, dedicated teams, partnerships, distribution
Platform incumbents	Zoom AI Companion, Microsoft Copilot, Google Meet "Take notes for me"	Already in the meeting. Free. Already trusted. Already integrated with calendar/docs/email
Horizontal AI	ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini — paste a transcript, get a summary	Free or already paid for. Zero switching cost
Vertical AI workspaces	Notion AI, Linear, Slack AI	Already where the outputs of meetings live
Question: what does your app know, see, own, or do that none of these can match?

If you can't answer that in one sentence, the answer is "build nothing." AI summarization is a commodity. You'd be selling water in a town where the river is free.

The hidden assumptions stacked under your one question
#	Assumption	Why it's risky
1	Our users have meetings (and we have access to them)	Do you? Do they happen in your app, or somewhere else (Zoom, Meet, Teams)? If elsewhere, you have an integration problem before you have a feature
2	Summarization is the most valuable AI use case for our users	Why summarization specifically? Why not action-item extraction, decision logs, follow-up drafting, search, coaching? Summarization is the least differentiated of the bunch
3	Users don't already have a summarization tool they prefer	Most professionals already use Otter, Granola, or Zoom's built-in. You'd be the third tool generating summaries from the same meeting
4	Summarization improves a metric we care about (retention, conversion, NPS, expansion)	Or is this a "we ship AI features" press-release feature? Be honest
5	We can build it cheaply enough	LLM API costs at scale, transcription costs, latency engineering, hallucination handling, privacy/compliance review — this is not a 2-sprint feature for a serious build
6	Privacy/legal will let us record customer meetings	This alone has killed dozens of meeting-AI initiatives in regulated industries. Have you talked to legal?
7	Our distribution advantage transfers to this feature	Just because users use your app for X doesn't mean they'll use it for meetings. Different jobs-to-be-done, different workflow moments
8	Building beats integrating	The contrarian move: don't build a summarizer — integrate with the one your users already use and pull insights into your app. Lower cost, higher leverage
That's 8 deadly assumptions under "what if we used AI to summarize meetings?" The one that kills the most projects is #7 — distribution doesn't transfer just because both products live on a screen.

Convert "what if" into a falsifiable hypothesis
❌ What you said:

"What if we made our app use AI to summarize meetings?"

That's not even a hypothesis. It's a daydream with a question mark.

✅ Forced into a 4-field contract:

Field	You'd need to fill in
Belief	We believe [which segment of our users], in [which workflow context], will [specific behavior — adopt/retain/pay more/refer] if we [specific intervention — record meetings? import transcripts? auto-trigger summaries?] because [specific job-to-be-done that nothing in their current stack solves].
Evidence needed	We'll be right if [specific metric] moves by [specific amount] within [window]. We'll be wrong if [specific kill criterion].
Experiment	Smallest possible test that produces signal in [time box ≤ 4 weeks] for [cost ≤ N eng-days].
Success criteria	A real number, a real denominator, a real date.
You cannot fill in those blanks right now, because you haven't done the upstream work. That's the diagnosis.

The bold version
Not "what if we used AI to summarize meetings?" — that's the safe, me-too, board-deck-friendly framing.

Try one of these:

Bold reframe	Why it's bolder
"What's the one piece of intelligence about our users' meetings — that we already have access to and competitors don't — that we could surface to change their behavior?"	Forces you to find an unfair advantage before committing to a build
"What if instead of summarizing meetings, we eliminated 30% of our users' meetings entirely by surfacing the decision they were going to make?"	Different theory of value: don't optimize the artifact, kill the activity
"What if we did not build AI features — and instead aggressively integrated with the AI tools our users already pay for?"	Tests whether your real role is summarizer or system of record for the outputs
"What's the AI feature an incumbent like Granola or Otter literally cannot copy in 6 weeks because of something structural about our product?"	Forces a defensibility-first frame before a feature-first frame
If you can't answer at least one of those, don't build the feature.

